  year      = {2024},
  doi       = {10.1177/03091325241289546},
  note      = {Critiques recent theorists who argue displacement violates place-based or located life-plans and should be rejected based on personal autonomy principles. Argues this attempt to value social attachments as means to realize plans is unconvincing and subject to moral risk because it instrumentalizes social attachments instead of recognizing their intrinsic significance. Provides alternative account of urban justice that accommodates respect for social attachments as separate moral category, distinct from respect for personal autonomy. Associate Professor in Political Theory at Radboud University, Nijmegen. Communitarian-inspired alternative to prevailing autonomy-based frameworks.}
